● Cough

Signs
● Tachypnoea;
● Agitation/cyanosis;
● Respiratory distress. There will be use of accessory muscles;
● Facial/airway trauma;
● Listen for type of breathing sounds;
● Snuffle - nasal obstruction, important in children;
● Stertor - “sounds like snoring” which suggests pharyngeal obstruction;
● Stridor (as described above);
● Wheeze - level of obstruction is intra-thoracic trachea or small airways. May occur in anaphylaxis;
● Decreased breath sounds - indicates acute decompensation / fatigue

Complications
● Respiratory arrest;
● Airway compromise must be recognised early. Children may decompensate rapidly.

